{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16389"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16389"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.26,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9080"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5921"},{"type":"tags","id":"7533"},{"type":"tags","id":"7555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21583"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic chiasm is an anatomical structure where nerve fibers from the retina partially cross on their path to the visual cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the visual field defect caused by a lesion at the optic chiasm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Complete monocular blindness","Binasal hemianopia","Superior quadrantanopia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic chiasm is the point where fibers from the nasal halves of each retina cross to the opposite side. A lesion at the optic chiasm typically causes \u003Cstrong\u003Ebitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because the crossing nasal retinal fibers from both eyes are damaged, while the uncrossed temporal fibers remain intact. Each nasal retina receives input from the temporal visual field, so damage to crossing nasal fibers results in loss of temporal vision in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with unilateral lesions posterior to the chiasm, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete monocular blindness\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with lesions of a single optic nerve before the chiasm. \u003Cstrong\u003EBinasal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E is rare and would require bilateral lesions affecting only uncrossed fibers, and \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with lesions in the temporal lobe affecting Meyer\u0027s loop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of chiasmal lesions is compression from a pituitary tumor, which typically grows upward to compress the central portion of the chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The optic chiasm is where nasal retinal fibers cross to the opposite side while temporal fibers remain uncrossed.","A lesion at the optic chiasm typically affects the crossing nasal fibers from both eyes, resulting in bitemporal hemianopia.","Common causes of chiasmal lesions include pituitary tumors, craniopharyngiomas, and meningiomas."],"references":["Freddi TAL, Ottaiano AC. The Optic Nerve: Anatomy and Pathology. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2022 Oct;43(5):378-388. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2022.04.006. Epub 2022 Apr 13. PMID: 36116850.","Takahashi M, Goseki T, Ishikawa H, Hiroyasu G, Hirasawa K, Shoji N. Compressive Lesions of the Optic Chiasm: Subjective Symptoms and Visual Field Diagnostic Criteria. Neuroophthalmology. 2018 Sep 11;42(6):343-348. doi: 10.1080/01658107.2018.1438477. PMID: 30524487; PMCID: PMC6276958.","Wall M. Perimetry and visual field defects. Handb Clin Neurol. 2021;178:51-77. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-12-821377-3.00003-9. PMID: 33832687.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16389"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T16:13:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T16:13:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9080"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":